Analysis of Sexual and/or Physical Violence on Women¶

Data Analyst Information¶

Data analyzed by: Gabriel S
Email: gabriel777sh@gmail.com

Brief¶

I'm interested in this dataset because I'm aware, that there are women / girls out there suffering from sexual / physical violence conducted by their partner (either it was intentional / unintentional).

I want to correct the awful misconception of "women are not equal to men, therefore they must behave / follow the men unconditionally". Let's pursue the gender equality!

Dataset¶

File : eliminationViolenceAgainstWomen.csv
Source : https://kaggle.com/utkarshxy

Characteristics¶

  • Location : Country of interest
  • Indicator : Proportion of ever-partnered women and girls aged 15-49 years subjected to physical and/or sexual violence by a current or former intimate partner in the previous 12 months
  • Dim1 : Gender
  • Dim2 : Age group
  • First tooltip (?) : percentage of subjects that receive sexual/physical violence

Data Merging¶

As we have seen here:

For this case, I want the datasets to be yearly. This means that the data representation will be assumed to be taken at the end of the year.

So I need to merge the category:

  • "2010-2011" : merge with "2011"
  • "2011-2012" : merge with "2012"
  • "2013-2014" : merge with "2014"
  • "2014-2015" : merge with "2015"
  • "2015-2016" : merge with "2016"
  • "2016-2017" : merge with "2017"
In [324]:
df_periods_merged = []
period_merge_pattern = {
    "2010-2011" : "2011",
    "2011-2012" : "2012",
    "2013-2014" : "2014",
    "2014-2015" : "2015",
    "2015-2016" : "2016",
    "2016-2017" : "2017",
}

for key, target in period_merge_pattern.items():
    # concat the data
    concated = pd.concat([
      df_main[ df_main["Period"] == key ],
      df_main[ df_main["Period"] == target ]
    ])
    
    # Get index of periods that has "yyyy-yyyy" format
    key_indexes = list(concated[ concated["Period"] == key].index)
    
    # Change "yyyy-yyyy" to "yyyy" format
    for index in key_indexes:
        concated.at[index, "Period"] = target
    
    # append to list of merged dataframes
    df_periods_merged.append(concated)

# Concat the data for good & check for duplicates
df_periods_merged = pd.concat(df_periods_merged)

display(df_periods_merged.duplicated().any())
display(df_periods_merged.head(5))

Merging the "normal datas" with the "processed data"¶

Here, I used outer join, since I assumed there's a possibility of duplicate datas if I used normal concatenation. This possibility arises since there are many overlapping periods when the data was taken.

I use outer join, because it's just the same as concating both the data & dropping the duplicate rows.

In [326]:
df_main_new = pd.merge(df_normal_datas, df_periods_merged, how="outer")

print(f"Duplicated data: {df_main_new.duplicated().any()}\n")
display(df_main_new.info())

End of data merging¶

And now, I'll have a clean datas, with non-null entries and no duplicates! Such clean datas are sophisticating to work on... But wait, there's something unique about the data! Yes, it's at the period: 2000. There's only 1 country that has percentage data, and also, after 2000, there's a huge time-gap until 2005. So in this case, I decide to drop the period 2000, and change my period of interest from 2005-2017.

In [327]:
df_main_new = df_main_new.drop(
    df_main_new[df_main_new["Period"] == "2000"].index

Global data for ease of calculation¶

# Total percentage of no violence
subjects_no_violence = 100.0 - np.array(df_main_new["Percentage"])
subjects_no_violence_sum = subjects_no_violence.sum()
print("Subjects that are NOT exposed to sexual / physical violence (cumulative %): ")
print(subjects_no_violence_sum)

# Total percentage of violence
subjects_with_violence = np.array(df_main_new["Percentage"])
subjects_with_violence_sum = subjects_with_violence.sum()
print("Subjects that are exposed to sexual / physical violence (cumulative %): ")
print(subjects_with_violence_sum)

# Total of all percentage
subjects_total = subjects_with_violence_sum + subjects_no_violence_sum
print("Total (cumulative %): ")
print(subjects_total)

Sexual/Physical Violence Throughout the Year¶

# Normalize the value
period_group = df_main_new.sort_values("Period")
# For labelling
years = period_group["Period"].drop_duplicates()

period_group = np.array(period_group.groupby("Period", sort=False).sum()).flatten()
period_group_relative = 100 * period_group / subjects_total


title_opts = {
    "fontsize" : 18,
    "fontweight" : "bold"
}

label_opts = {
    "fontsize" : 16,
}

plt.figure(1, figsize=(14,8))
plt.bar(years, period_group_relative)
plt.title("Percentage of Women Exposed to Sexual / Physical Violence per Year", fontdict=title_opts)
plt.xlabel("Year", fontdict=label_opts)
plt.ylabel("Percentage", fontdict=label_opts)
plt.grid(axis="y")
plt.show()

country_group = np.array(df_main_new.groupby("Countries").sum()).flatten()

countries = df_main_new["Countries"].drop_duplicates()

title_opts = {
    "fontsize" : 18,
    "fontweight" : "bold"
}

}

plt.figure(1, figsize=(20,40))

plt.grid("both", axis="x")
plt.show()
Percentage of Physical / Sexual Violence by Age Group per Year¶

Relative to the total women in the populace (women that are not subjected to the analysis are not counted)

In [336]:
age_groups = df_main_new.groupby(["Period", "Age Group"], as_index=False).sum()

age_group_dict = {}
age_group_keys = [f"{x}" for x in range(2005, 2018)]

# Plotting options
fig_count = 0 
title_opts = {
    "fontweight" : "bold",
    "fontsize" : 16
}

label_opts = {
    "fontsize" : 14
}

for period in age_group_keys:
    fig_count += 1
    data = age_groups[
        age_groups["Period"] == period
    ]
    
    data_np_arr = np.array(data["Percentage"])
    data_np_arr = 100 * data_np_arr / subjects_total
    data_labels = np.array(data["Age Group"])
    
    plt.figure(fig_count, figsize=(14, 8))
    plt.bar(data_labels, data_np_arr)
    plt.title(period, fontdict=title_opts)
    plt.xlabel("Age Groups", fontdict=label_opts)
    plt.ylabel("Percentage", fontdict=label_opts)
    plt.grid(axis="y")
    
plt.show()
